MODERN WARFIGHTING AND THE DECLINE OF THE COLD WAR DOCTRINE [3]
THE AGE OF MASS IS OVER.
BY: ANDREW DAVIDSON
For more than a generation, the international system was organized along the lines of the Cold War. Though the United States and the Soviet Union were the primary belligerents in the conflict, the
foreign policies of nearly all nations were conceived through the lens of the Cold War. Naturally, this resulted in a bespoke military doctrine.
The doctrine was built for a specific kind of war: one fought between industrial superpowers across well-defined fronts with massive armies, heavy armor and deep logistical lines. It assumed time to
mobilize, the ability to mass forces and relatively secure rear areas. Military power was measured in divisions, tanks and firepower. Volume mattered more than precision.
This model fit the structure of a bipolar world, one characterized by static alliance blocs, clearly defined borders and predictable escalation patterns. Even after the collapse of the Soviet Union,
the model persisted. Without a near-peer threat to force structural change, the U.S. retained its global garrison posture and logistics-heavy force design. The post-9/11 wars reinforced large-scale
logistics networks, forward operating bases and centralized command structures – keeping the Cold War logic alive even in asymmetric environments. Yet even in Iraq and Afghanistan, where the
adversary lacked mass and maneuverability, the U.S. often relied on static bases, armored patrols and top-down command. This mismatch between Cold War force design and irregular threats undermined
long-term strategic success. Conventional formations and centralized logistics sustained the fight, but they encouraged static operations, predictable patterns and strategic rigidity.
But the 21st-century battlefield has changed. The proliferation of precision-guided munitions, persistent satellite and drone surveillance, and the rise of cyber and electronic warfare have rendered
massed forces vulnerable before they engage. Enemies can now strike deep, they can blind command and control networks, and they can expose large formations in real time. Rear areas are no longer
sanctuaries; they are targets.
Recent conflicts, especially in Ukraine and in the Indo-Pacific, have accelerated this shift. The era of mass is giving way to mobility, deception and integrated kill chains. The new model demands
dispersion, survivability and digital integration across contested domains.
OBSOLESCENCE
The Cold War model was rooted not only in doctrine, but in force structure and geography. Victory depended on the ability to deploy and sustain large, heavily equipped formations – divisions of
troops, tanks, artillery and support units – operating from permanent garrisons and supplied by centralized logistics hubs. Military success rested on the ability to overwhelm adversaries through
depth and firepower.
Strategic geography reinforced the model. Battlefields were envisioned as linear and static, centered on chokepoints for enemy thrusts. U.S. and allied forces were forward-deployed in fixed positions,
relying on geographic predictability to deter aggression and enable rapid response. But this rigidity locked force posture into brittle assumptions about the predictability of geography, time to
mobilize and rear safety.
These assumptions shaped the doctrines that followed. The U.S. AirLand Battle doctrine, for example, replaced the short-lived Active Defense doctrine of the 1970s, which focused on stopping a Soviet
assault through linear defense. Active Defense was widely seen as too static and attritional, prompting the Army to adopt a more aggressive, deep-strike concept in 1982. AirLand Battle did not replace
the logic of mass; it refined it. Despite its focus on simultaneity and deep strikes, it still assumed conventional formations, secure communications and uncontested logistics corridors. Its
operational effectiveness depended on centralized decision-making and structured battlespaces – conditions increasingly incompatible with a transparent, strike-saturated environment.
Following the Cold War, AirLand Battle evolved into Full-Spectrum Operations, formalized in 2001 to encompass peace enforcement, stability operations and conventional combat. But the foundational
logic of mass, centralized logistics and domain-specific command endured. It still worked because it still functioned under the conditions of rear-area security, uncontested air dominance and
prolonged timelines for buildup. The U.S. military retained its global garrison posture and legacy systems because no near-peer threat forced doctrinal or structural overhaul. Instead, Cold War-era
systems were repurposed for new missions from the Balkans to Iraq and Afghanistan, reinforcing large operating bases, long logistical tails and centralized control. The model’s utility sufficed for
the demands of protracted occupations in the post-9/11 wars, though over time it became increasingly clear that the model no longer matched the emerging threat environment.
