The result was an obsolete force model optimized for an obsolete kind of warfare. The Cold War model was designed for opacity, sanctuary and scale. Continuous surveillance, precision weapons and
rapid-strike capabilities have collapsed the window for buildup and erased the rear as a safe zone. The Cold War model’s strength, its mass, has become a liability under modern conditions that
demand transparency and speed.
The information environment has fundamentally changed too. Cold War-era concealment and deception were viable at scale. Satellite coverage was infrequent, resolution limited and tactical intelligence
slow. Today’s battlespace, saturated as it is with commercial ISR (intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance) platforms, drones and open-source intelligence, renders operational security and
surprise nearly obsolete. Large movements are now detectable, and logistics networks are exposed in real time.
New domains have emerged to exploit these vulnerabilities. Cyber and electronic warfare now target the connective tissue of modern militaries: logistics networks, command systems and decision
architecture.
Warfare today favors speed, dispersion and digital adaptation. The Russia-Ukraine war has tested the Cold War model in real time and exposed its vulnerabilities. Russia entered the conflict with a
doctrine rooted in Soviet-era operational logic despite being tactically modernized with drones, electronic warfare and some networking. Ukrainian forces, backed by Western ISR and precision weapons,
operated with agility and dispersion, targeting Russian formations, depots and command and control nodes in real time. Rear areas proved vulnerable. Electronic warfare blinded drones and severed
communications. Both sides found that mass without survivability led to losses, and movement without concealment invited strikes. The limited maneuver on the battlefield reflects not stagnation but
the collapse of assumptions that once enabled large-scale operations.
That the Russia-Ukraine war has featured trench lines, artillery duels and territorial attrition has invited comparisons to 20th-century warfare, but the comparison is misleading. The war is not a
revival of Cold War doctrine; it is a transitional conflict that reveals why the legacy model no longer holds. Ukraine’s ability to hold ground has depended not on mass but on agility, decentralized
kill chains and rapid adaptation. The Russia-Ukraine war is instructive not because attrition returned but because it is now shaped by precision and transparency.
In this environment, relying on the Cold War model is no longer just inefficient – it's operationally dangerous. Recognizing the vulnerabilities of legacy force structures in a transparent,
high-threat environment, the United States has begun reorienting its military doctrine and operational concepts toward survivability, dispersion and cross-domain integration. This new model reflects a
fundamental shift in how military power is generated, sustained and applied under conditions of nonstop surveillance, cyber disruption and long-range targeting capabilities.
REFORM
The U.S. military has thus undertaken structural and doctrinal reforms to reduce its dependence on mass and static infrastructure while increasing its ability to operate in contested, data-rich
environments. The Air Force’s Agile Combat Employment concept emphasizes rapid dispersal to austere or civilian airfields, mobile support teams and pre-positioned fuel and munitions. It’s designed
to complicate adversary targeting and ensure continuity of air operations under missile or electromagnetic threat. The concept is already being stress-tested in exercises like REFORPAC 2025, the
largest Air Force Pacific drill in decades, involving more than 300 aircraft in more than 50 locations to demonstrate real-time dispersed operations across six time zones.
The Marine Corps, through Force Design 2030, has restructured around archipelagic and littoral warfare, marking a shift from its recent use as a second land army. Tanks and heavy artillery are being
phased out in favor of Marine Littoral Regiments – small, highly mobile units capable of operating inside contested maritime zones and executing distributed kill chains. These forces are optimized
for speed, low signature and integration with naval and joint fires.
The U.S. Army’s Multi-Domain Operations doctrine treats land, air, space, cyber and the electromagnetic spectrum as a single, integrated battlespace. It prioritizes long-range precision fire,
cross-domain maneuver and real-time data flows to achieve decision advantage. Instead of traditional armored thrusts, dispersed units leverage sensors and networks to deny or disrupt adversary
capabilities before close contact.
Meanwhile, the U.S. Navy has embraced Distributed Maritime Operations to increase fleet survivability and operational unpredictability. This includes a growing role for smaller combatants, unmanned
platforms and decentralized command and control.
The Competitive Endurance doctrine the Space Force uses recognizes space as a domain that is no longer safe due to anti-satellite weapons. Its strategy emphasizes resilience through satellite
disaggregation, reconstitution and integration with joint and commercial space networks to maintain access under contested conditions.
At the institutional level, the Department of Defense is investing in Joint All-Domain Command and Control (JADC2) and its multinational counterpart (CJADC2), replacing legacy hierarchical systems
with dynamic sensor-to-shooter networks. These architectures aim to connect platforms and units across services, allies and domains in real time, enabling faster targeting cycles and decentralized
decision-making.
The doctrinal shift underway is already being operationalized through defense-industrial adaptation. The Pentagon’s pivot toward resilient, modular and software-defined systems is reshaping
procurement priorities. Legacy acquisition timelines are under pressure as services demand systems that can be updated rapidly, deployed flexibly and scaled across dispersed formations. The emphasis
on unmanned systems, open architectures and multi-mission payloads reflects a growing alignment between operational concepts and industrial capacity. Recent legislation, including the “Big Beautiful
Bill” and its Section 2000-series authorities, reinforces this momentum by expanding multiyear procurement to support high-attrition next-generation systems.
THE FUTURE
These efforts are paving the way for a fundamentally different force design. The U.S. and its allies are now building for wars defined by speed, dispersion and integration. This does not mean mass is
irrelevant. As the Russia-Ukraine war has shown, total force size and sustained manpower still matter, but mass can no longer be concentrated as it once was. Survivability now requires dispersing mass
across networks, nodes and domains to avoid detection and destruction.
In a world where satellites and long-range strike capabilities compress time and erase freedom of maneuver on the rear lines, military advantage belongs to those who can sense, decide and act faster
than their adversary. Power is measured by the speed and resilience of networks connecting sensors, shooters and decision-makers across domains.
Future forces will be dispersed, mobile and low-signature, constantly shifting configurations to complicate enemy targeting. Drones, autonomous platforms and modular ISR systems will dominate ISR and
strike missions. Kill chains will prioritize small, adaptable units able to plug into joint networks and deliver effects in seconds rather than hours. Large, permanent bases will give way to flexible
“lily pad” networks that support distributed operations from austere locations.
Strategically, the model demands more than new platforms. It requires reimagining command and control: data-centric architectures, automated decision aids and AI-augmented targeting to function in
high-tempo environments. Rather than seeking dominance in a single domain, the goal is cross-domain advantage where space, cyber and the electromagnetic spectrum shape outcomes on land and sea before
the first shot is fired.
But doctrine alone cannot drive this shift. It also requires an industrial base designed for scale, speed and adaptability. Systems like loitering munitions, counter-drone platforms and mobile
logistics kits are essential, but they cannot be built on Cold War-era procurement timelines. The age of mass is over. The age of maneuver, networks and resilience has begun. Strategy and structure
must match reality.
