<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">For more than a ge=
neration, the international system was organized along the lines of the Col=
d War. Though the United States and the Soviet Union were the primary belli=
gerents in the conflict, the foreign policies of nearly all nations were co=
nceived through the lens of the Cold War. Naturally, this resulted in a bes=
poke military doctrine.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The doctrine was b=
uilt for a specific kind of war: one fought between industrial superpowers =
across well-defined fronts with massive armies, heavy armor and deep logist=
ical lines. It assumed time to mobilize, the ability to mass forces and rel=
atively secure rear areas. Military power was measured in divisions, tanks =
and firepower. Volume mattered more than precision.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">This model fit the=
 structure of a bipolar world, one characterized by static alliance blocs, =
clearly defined borders and predictable escalation patterns. Even after the=
 collapse of the Soviet Union, the model persisted. Without a near-peer thr=
eat to force structural change, the U.S. retained its global garrison postu=
re and logistics-heavy force design. The post-9/11 wars reinforced large-sc=
ale logistics networks, forward operating bases and centralized command str=
uctures =E2=80=93 keeping the Cold War logic alive even in asymmetric envir=
onments. Yet even in Iraq and Afghanistan, where the adversary lacked mass =
and maneuverability, the U.S. often relied on static bases, armored patrols=
 and top-down command. This mismatch between Cold War force design and irre=
gular threats undermined long-term strategic success. Conventional formatio=
ns and centralized logistics sustained the fight, but they encouraged stati=
c operations, predictable patterns and strategic rigidity.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">But the 21st-centu=
ry battlefield has changed. The proliferation of precision-guided munitions=
, persistent satellite and drone surveillance, and the rise of cyber and el=
ectronic warfare have rendered massed forces vulnerable before they engage.=
 Enemies can now strike deep, they can blind command and control networks, =
and they can expose large formations in real time. Rear areas are no longer=
 sanctuaries; they are targets.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Recent conflicts, =
especially in Ukraine and in the Indo-Pacific, have accelerated this shift.=
 The era of mass is giving way to mobility, deception and integrated kill c=
hains. The new model demands dispersion, survivability and digital integrat=
ion across contested domains.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0"><strong>Obsolescen=
ce</strong></p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The Cold War model=
 was rooted not only in doctrine, but in force structure and geography. Vic=
tory depended on the ability to deploy and sustain large, heavily equipped =
formations =E2=80=93 divisions of troops, tanks, artillery and support unit=
s =E2=80=93 operating from permanent garrisons and supplied by centralized =
logistics hubs. Military success rested on the ability to overwhelm adversa=
ries through depth and firepower.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Strategic geograph=
y reinforced the model. Battlefields were envisioned as linear and static, =
centered on chokepoints for enemy thrusts. U.S. and allied forces were forw=
ard-deployed in fixed positions, relying on geographic predictability to de=
ter aggression and enable rapid response. But this rigidity locked force po=
sture into brittle assumptions about the predictability of geography, time =
to mobilize and rear safety.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">These assumptions =
shaped the doctrines that followed. The U.S. AirLand Battle doctrine, for e=
xample, replaced the short-lived Active Defense doctrine of the 1970s, whic=
h focused on stopping a Soviet assault through linear defense. Active Defen=
se was widely seen as too static and attritional, prompting the Army to ado=
pt a more aggressive, deep-strike concept in 1982. AirLand Battle did not r=
eplace the logic of mass; it refined it. Despite its focus on simultaneity =
and deep strikes, it still assumed conventional formations, secure communic=
ations and uncontested logistics corridors. Its operational effectiveness d=
epended on centralized decision-making and structured battlespaces =E2=80=
=93 conditions increasingly incompatible with a transparent, strike-saturat=
ed environment.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Following the Cold=
 War, AirLand Battle evolved into Full-Spectrum Operations, formalized in 2=
001 to encompass peace enforcement, stability operations and conventional c=
ombat. But the foundational logic of mass, centralized logistics and domain=
-specific command endured. It still worked because it still functioned unde=
r the conditions of rear-area security, uncontested air dominance and prolo=
nged timelines for buildup. The U.S. military retained its global garrison =
posture and legacy systems because no near-peer threat forced doctrinal or =
structural overhaul. Instead, Cold War-era systems were repurposed for new =
missions from the Balkans to Iraq and Afghanistan, reinforcing large operat=
ing bases, long logistical tails and centralized control. The model=E2=80=
=99s utility sufficed for the demands of protracted occupations in the post=
-9/11 wars, though over time it became increasingly clear that the model no=
 longer matched the emerging threat environment.</p>
