<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The result was an =
obsolete force model optimized for an obsolete kind of warfare. The Cold Wa=
r model was designed for opacity, sanctuary and scale. Continuous surveilla=
nce, precision weapons and rapid-strike capabilities have collapsed the win=
dow for buildup and erased the rear as a safe zone. The Cold War model=E2=
=80=99s strength, its mass, has become a liability under modern conditions =
that demand transparency and speed.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The information en=
vironment has fundamentally changed too. Cold War-era concealment and decep=
tion were viable at scale. Satellite coverage was infrequent, resolution li=
mited and tactical intelligence slow. Today=E2=80=99s battlespace, saturate=
d as it is with commercial ISR (intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissan=
ce) platforms, drones and open-source intelligence, renders operational sec=
urity and surprise nearly obsolete. Large movements are now detectable, and=
 logistics networks are exposed in real time.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">New domains have e=
merged to exploit these vulnerabilities. Cyber and electronic warfare now t=
arget the connective tissue of modern militaries: logistics networks, comma=
nd systems and decision architecture.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Warfare today favo=
rs speed, dispersion and digital adaptation. The Russia-Ukraine war has tes=
ted the Cold War model in real time and exposed its vulnerabilities. Russia=
 entered the conflict with a doctrine rooted in Soviet-era operational logi=
c despite being tactically modernized with drones, electronic warfare and s=
ome networking. Ukrainian forces, backed by Western ISR and precision weapo=
ns, operated with agility and dispersion, targeting Russian formations, dep=
ots and command and control nodes in real time. Rear areas proved vulnerabl=
e. Electronic warfare blinded drones and severed communications. Both sides=
 found that mass without survivability led to losses, and movement without =
concealment invited strikes. The limited maneuver on the battlefield reflec=
ts not stagnation but the collapse of assumptions that once enabled large-s=
cale operations.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">That the Russia-Uk=
raine war has featured trench lines, artillery duels and territorial attrit=
ion has invited comparisons to 20th-century warfare, but the comparison is =
misleading. The war is not a revival of Cold War doctrine; it is a transiti=
onal conflict that reveals why the legacy model no longer holds. Ukraine=E2=
=80=99s ability to hold ground has depended not on mass but on agility, dec=
entralized kill chains and rapid adaptation. The Russia-Ukraine war is inst=
ructive not because attrition returned but because it is now shaped by prec=
ision and transparency.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">In this environmen=
t, relying on the Cold War model is no longer just inefficient =E2=80=93 it=
's operationally dangerous. Recognizing the vulnerabilities of legacy force=
 structures in a transparent, high-threat environment, the United States ha=
s begun reorienting its military doctrine and operational concepts toward s=
urvivability, dispersion and cross-domain integration. This new model refle=
cts a fundamental shift in how military power is generated, sustained and a=
pplied under conditions of nonstop surveillance, cyber disruption and long-=
range targeting capabilities.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0"><strong>Reform</st=
rong></p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The U.S. military =
has thus undertaken structural and doctrinal reforms to reduce its dependen=
ce on mass and static infrastructure while increasing its ability to operat=
e in contested, data-rich environments. The Air Force=E2=80=99s Agile Comba=
t Employment concept emphasizes rapid dispersal to austere or civilian airf=
ields, mobile support teams and pre-positioned fuel and munitions. It=E2=80=
=99s designed to complicate adversary targeting and ensure continuity of ai=
r operations under missile or electromagnetic threat. The concept is alread=
y being stress-tested in exercises like REFORPAC 2025, the largest Air Forc=
e Pacific drill in decades, involving more than 300 aircraft in more than 5=
0 locations to demonstrate real-time dispersed operations across six time z=
ones.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The Marine Corps, =
through Force Design 2030, has restructured around archipelagic and littora=
l warfare, marking a shift from its recent use as a second land army. Tanks=
 and heavy artillery are being phased out in favor of Marine Littoral Regim=
ents =E2=80=93 small, highly mobile units capable of operating inside conte=
sted maritime zones and executing distributed kill chains. These forces are=
 optimized for speed, low signature and integration with naval and joint fi=
res.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The U.S. Army=E2=
=80=99s Multi-Domain Operations doctrine treats land, air, space, cyber and=
 the electromagnetic spectrum as a single, integrated battlespace. It prior=
itizes long-range precision fire, cross-domain maneuver and real-time data =
flows to achieve decision advantage. Instead of traditional armored thrusts=
, dispersed units leverage sensors and networks to deny or disrupt adversar=
y capabilities before close contact.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Meanwhile, the U.S=
. Navy has embraced Distributed Maritime Operations to increase fleet survi=
vability and operational unpredictability. This includes a growing role for=
 smaller combatants, unmanned platforms and decentralized command and contr=
ol.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The Competitive En=
durance doctrine the Space Force uses recognizes space as a domain that is =
no longer safe due to anti-satellite weapons. Its strategy emphasizes resil=
ience through satellite disaggregation, reconstitution and integration with=
 joint and commercial space networks to maintain access under contested con=
ditions.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">At the institution=
al level, the Department of Defense is investing in Joint All-Domain Comman=
d and Control (JADC2) and its multinational counterpart (CJADC2), replacing=
 legacy hierarchical systems with dynamic sensor-to-shooter networks. These=
 architectures aim to connect platforms and units across services, allies a=
nd domains in real time, enabling faster targeting cycles and decentralized=
 decision-making.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The doctrinal shif=
t underway is already being operationalized through defense-industrial adap=
tation. The Pentagon=E2=80=99s pivot toward resilient, modular and software=
-defined systems is reshaping procurement priorities. Legacy acquisition ti=
melines are under pressure as services demand systems that can be updated r=
apidly, deployed flexibly and scaled across dispersed formations. The empha=
sis on unmanned systems, open architectures and multi-mission payloads refl=
ects a growing alignment between operational concepts and industrial capaci=
ty. Recent legislation, including the =E2=80=9CBig Beautiful Bill=E2=80=9D =
and its Section 2000-series authorities, reinforces this momentum by expand=
ing multiyear procurement to support high-attrition next-generation systems=
.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0"><strong>The Future=
</strong></p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">These efforts are =
paving the way for a fundamentally different force design. The U.S. and its=
 allies are now building for wars defined by speed, dispersion and integrat=
ion. This does not mean mass is irrelevant. As the Russia-Ukraine war has s=
hown, total force size and sustained manpower still matter, but mass can no=
 longer be concentrated as it once was. Survivability now requires dispersi=
ng mass across networks, nodes and domains to avoid detection and destructi=
on.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">In a world where s=
atellites and long-range strike capabilities compress time and erase freedo=
m of maneuver on the rear lines, military advantage belongs to those who ca=
n sense, decide and act faster than their adversary. Power is measured by t=
he speed and resilience of networks connecting sensors, shooters and decisi=
on-makers across domains.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Future forces will=
 be dispersed, mobile and low-signature, constantly shifting configurations=
 to complicate enemy targeting. Drones, autonomous platforms and modular IS=
R systems will dominate ISR and strike missions. Kill chains will prioritiz=
e small, adaptable units able to plug into joint networks and deliver effec=
ts in seconds rather than hours. Large, permanent bases will give way to fl=
exible =E2=80=9Clily pad=E2=80=9D networks that support distributed operati=
ons from austere locations.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Strategically, the=
 model demands more than new platforms. It requires reimagining command and=
 control: data-centric architectures, automated decision aids and AI-augmen=
ted targeting to function in high-tempo environments. Rather than seeking d=
ominance in a single domain, the goal is cross-domain advantage where space=
, cyber and the electromagnetic spectrum shape outcomes on land and sea bef=
ore the first shot is fired.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">But doctrine alone=
 cannot drive this shift. It also requires an industrial base designed for =
scale, speed and adaptability. Systems like loitering munitions, counter-dr=
one platforms and mobile logistics kits are essential, but they cannot be b=
uilt on Cold War-era procurement timelines. The age of mass is over. The ag=
e of maneuver, networks and resilience has begun. Strategy and structure mu=
st match reality.</p>

